<h1>MAIDCONNECT — Mobile Platform Adoption Report</h1>
<p class="meta"><strong>Document type:</strong> Strategic adoption &amp; platform architecture report<br>
<strong>Prepared for:</strong> Olircore / MAIDCONNECT product vision — “Build a business as a mobile”<br>
<strong>Based on:</strong> Current HTML prototype (<code>maid-management-system.html</code>) and architecture review<br>
<strong>Date:</strong> July 5, 2026<br>
<strong>Scope:</strong> How to evolve MAIDCONNECT into a multi-company, multi-model mobile platform where apps function independently yet stay linked through shared records</p>

<div class="box">
<strong>Core idea in one sentence:</strong> Keep <em>departments and record types</em> stable across all companies, but let each company choose an <em>operational model</em> (workflow rules, stages, payment gates, task routing) — delivered as separate mobile-capable apps that all read/write the same linked data graph through APIs and events.
</div>

<h2>1. Executive Summary</h2>
<p>Your vision — independent apps linked to shared models, with different companies running different operational models while major departments remain the same — is a <strong>multi-tenant modular ERP platform</strong>, not a single monolithic app. MAIDCONNECT’s current prototype already demonstrates the right <em>conceptual</em> shape: module-based UI, canonical domain records (<code>MaidConnectERP</code>), cross-module workflow propagation, role-based access, and dual portals (agency + customer).</p>
<p>To adopt this vision, MAIDCONNECT should be re-platformed in three layers:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Stable platform core</strong> — tenants (companies), users, roles, departments, master entities, IDs, audit, permissions.</li>
  <li><strong>Configurable operational models</strong> — per-tenant workflow templates (request stages, payment gates, task rules, department handoffs).</li>
  <li><strong>Independent experience apps</strong> — mobile-first surfaces (Maid App, Request App, Finance App, Customer App, etc.) that own UX but never own duplicate business data.</li>
</ol>
<p>The prototype is an excellent <strong>requirements and UX validation artifact</strong>. It is not yet a mobile platform. This report defines how to bridge that gap without throwing away what you have already proven.</p>

<h2>2. Your Vision — Decoded into Platform Terms</h2>

<h3>2.1 “Build a business as a mobile”</h3>
<p>This does not mean “one giant mobile app with every feature.” It means:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Each <strong>department’s daily work</strong> is available on mobile (or mobile-first web) as a focused experience.</li>
  <li>Staff can complete real operations away from a desk: assign maids, confirm payments, reply inquiries, complete tasks, update request status.</li>
  <li>Customers interact through a <strong>Customer Mobile App</strong> (profiles, requests, payments, status) — already prototyped in the customer portal.</li>
  <li>The platform backend is the business; mobile apps are <strong>thin clients</strong> over shared APIs.</li>
</ul>

<h3>2.2 “Apps which function independently”</h3>
<p>Independent means:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Independent (allowed)</th><th>Not independent (forbidden)</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Separate deployable UI (own navigation, screens, offline cache)</td><td>Separate copy of Request, Customer, or Payment data</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Own release cycle per app team</td><td>Own conflicting status or payment state</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Can work when other apps are down (read cached + queue writes)</td><td>Direct database access to another module’s tables</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Department-specific UX optimized for field work</td><td>Duplicate workflow logic that diverges over time</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.3 “Linked to other models”</h3>
<p>All apps connect through <strong>canonical records and IDs</strong>, exactly as your prototype now defines conceptually:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>REQUEST.customerId</code>, <code>REQUEST.maidIds</code></li>
  <li><code>SHARE.customerId</code>, <code>SHARE.maidId</code>, <code>SHARE.requestId</code></li>
  <li><code>PAYMENT.requestId</code>, <code>TASK.requestId</code></li>
  <li><code>INQUIRY</code> → converted <code>REQUEST</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Apps do not embed full Customer or Maid profiles inside Request screens; they <strong>link</strong> to them (as your cleaned Request Management UI now does).</p>

<h3>2.4 “Different companies use different models”</h3>
<p>Two companies can both have Customer Relations, Maid Arrangement, Customer Care, and Finance — but:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Company A</strong> may require advance payment before any matching (your payment gate pattern).</li>
  <li><strong>Company B</strong> may allow matching first, invoice later.</li>
  <li><strong>Company C</strong> may use a 6-stage pipeline; <strong>Company D</strong> may use 10 stages including separate medical and training gates.</li>
</ul>
<p>Departments stay the same; <strong>workflow configuration</strong> changes per tenant.</p>

<h2>3. What the Current Prototype Already Gives You</h2>
<p>Your HTML prototype and recent architecture cleanup established patterns that map directly to a platform plan:</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Prototype asset</th><th>Platform equivalent</th><th>Readiness</th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MC_MODULES</code> (Dashboard, Maid, Customer, Request, Finance, Supplier, Tasks, Reports, Admin)</td><td>Product module registry + app boundaries</td><td>Strong concept</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MaidConnectERP.state</code> (orders, maids, customers, shares, inquiries)</td><td>Core domain services + database schemas</td><td>Partial — needs backend persistence</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>RequestAPI</code> — single Request record with projections</td><td>Request service as system of record; portal/agency as views</td><td>Strong pattern (recently cleaned)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MC_ACCESS</code> + roles (CR, Maid Arrangement, Customer Care, Finance, Admin)</td><td>Central RBAC / policy engine</td><td>Good demo; needs server enforcement</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MC_TEAMS</code> + cross-department tasks</td><td>Task service with department assignment without ownership transfer</td><td>Good operational pattern</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>WorkflowEngine.propagate()</code></td><td>Event bus (domain events → module refresh)</td><td>Seed pattern for micro-frontend / multi-app sync</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Agency portal + Customer portal</td><td>Two app families on same platform</td><td>Proven UX split</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Payment gate on Request progression</td><td>Configurable business rule per tenant</td><td>Proven rule type</td></tr>
</table>

<p><strong>Key lesson from the prototype:</strong> The product works when one authoritative record exists per business object and every module is a <em>view + action surface</em> over that record. This is the non-negotiable foundation for your multi-app plan.</p>

<h2>4. Target Platform Architecture</h2>

<h3>4.1 Logical architecture</h3>
<p>Recommended target (conceptual):</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Platform Core (Olircore Platform)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Tenant management (company onboarding, branding, locale, currency)</li>
      <li>Identity &amp; access (users, roles, departments, device sessions)</li>
      <li>Master data registry (entity types, ID formats, link rules)</li>
      <li>Audit, notifications, file storage metadata</li>
      <li>Operational model engine (workflow templates, stage maps, rules)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Domain Services (linked models — one owner each)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Maid Service — profile, recruitment, supplier link, training, publication</li>
      <li>Customer Service — CRM profile, communications, history</li>
      <li>Request Service — single request/order record, status, department ownership</li>
      <li>Share Service — visibility between customer and maid profiles</li>
      <li>Inquiry Service — pre-request conversations</li>
      <li>Finance Service — invoices, payments, refunds, outstanding</li>
      <li>Task Service — cross-department work queue</li>
      <li>Supplier Service — supplier master, bills, internal costs</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Experience Apps (mobile / web — independent deploy)</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>Agency Ops App (or split per department)</li>
      <li>Maid Management App</li>
      <li>Request Work Queue App</li>
      <li>Finance App</li>
      <li>Customer Mobile App</li>
      <li>Admin / Configuration App</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Integration Layer</strong>
    <ul>
      <li>REST/GraphQL APIs + webhooks</li>
      <li>Domain event stream (e.g. <code>request.maid.assigned</code>, <code>payment.confirmed</code>)</li>
      <li>Optional sync for offline mobile (local queue → server reconcile)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h3>4.2 Data linking model (from prototype to production)</h3>
<p>Carry forward the prototype’s entity graph as the platform contract:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Entity</th><th>Owned by</th><th>Linked to</th><th>Apps that read</th><th>Apps that write</th></tr>
  <tr><td>MAID</td><td>Maid Service</td><td>Supplier, Shares, Requests</td><td>All agency apps, Customer (shared view)</td><td>Maid App, Maid Arrangement actions in Request App</td></tr>
  <tr><td>CUSTOMER</td><td>Customer Service</td><td>Requests, Inquiries, Payments, Shares</td><td>CRM, Request, Finance, Customer App</td><td>CRM App, Customer App (profile)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>REQUEST</td><td>Request Service</td><td>Customer, Maids, Payments, Tasks, Inquiries</td><td>Request, Finance, Customer, Reports</td><td>Request App (status, assignment coordination)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>SHARE</td><td>Share Service</td><td>Customer, Maid, Request</td><td>Maid Sharing UI, Customer App</td><td>CRM / Maid Arrangement</td></tr>
  <tr><td>INQUIRY</td><td>Inquiry Service</td><td>Customer, Maid → Request on convert</td><td>CRM, Request</td><td>CRM, Customer App</td></tr>
  <tr><td>PAYMENT</td><td>Finance Service</td><td>Request, Customer</td><td>Finance, Request summary, Customer App</td><td>Finance App</td></tr>
  <tr><td>TASK</td><td>Task Service</td><td>Request, Department, Staff</td><td>Tasks App, Request detail</td><td>Any department (create); assignee (complete)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>SUPPLIER</td><td>Supplier Service</td><td>Maids, internal costs</td><td>Maid, Finance</td><td>Supplier App</td></tr>
</table>

<p><strong>Rule:</strong> Request Management <em>coordinates</em>; it does not store Maid recruitment data, full Customer CRM, or full Finance ledgers. Your prototype cleanup already moved in this direction.</p>

<div class="pagebreak"></div>

<h2>5. Stable Departments vs Configurable Operational Models</h2>

<h3>5.1 What stays the same for every company (platform standard)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Stable element</th><th>Why stable</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Major departments: Customer Relations, Maid Arrangement, Customer Care, Finance</td><td>Your apps, roles, and reports align to these; staff training transfers across tenants</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Core entity types: Maid, Customer, Request, Share, Inquiry, Payment, Task, Supplier</td><td>Enables shared integrations, analytics, and mobile SDKs</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Linking rules (IDs, foreign keys, event payloads)</td><td>Apps remain interoperable</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Permission dimensions: module visibility, page access, action rights</td><td>One RBAC model; tenant configures role packs</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Audit trail on state changes</td><td>Compliance and dispute resolution</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>5.2 What varies per company (tenant configuration)</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Configurable element</th><th>Example</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Request pipeline stages</td><td>6-step vs 10-step; skip “Training” for some markets</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Payment gate rules</td><td>Advance required before matching vs after assignment</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Department ownership rules</td><td>When request ownership transfers vs task-only handoff</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Maid publication rules</td><td>Internal approval before share; photo requirements</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Task templates</td><td>“Match 5 maids” auto-created on request submit</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Enabled modules</td><td>Company without Supplier module; Company with Reports only for HQ</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Branding, currency, tax, document templates</td><td>UAE agency vs Oman agency vs holding group</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Integration pack</td><td>Zoho Books vs Xero vs local accounting</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>5.3 Operational Model Profile (recommended configuration object)</h3>
<p>Define per tenant an <strong>Operational Model Profile</strong> (OMP) — a versioned JSON/document stored in Platform Core:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>pipelineId</code> — stage list and labels (maps to your <code>deploymentFlow</code>)</li>
  <li><code>paymentGatePolicy</code> — when advance is required; override roles</li>
  <li><code>ownershipPolicy</code> — when department ownership moves vs task delegation</li>
  <li><code>modulePack</code> — enabled modules and default role mappings</li>
  <li><code>taskTemplates</code> — auto-tasks by trigger (request created, maid assigned, etc.)</li>
  <li><code>mobilePack</code> — which apps are licensed for this tenant</li>
</ul>
<p>Company A and Company B share departments and entity types but load different OMPs. Apps read OMP at login and render the correct stages, gates, and enabled actions — exactly as your prototype’s role switcher demos permissions, but persisted per tenant.</p>

<h2>6. App Decomposition Strategy</h2>

<h3>6.1 From prototype modules to independent apps</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Prototype module</th><th>Future app(s)</th><th>Primary users</th><th>Mobile priority</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Dashboard</td><td>Agency Home App (widget shell)</td><td>All roles</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Maid Management + Sharing</td><td>Maid App (internal) + Share actions in CRM App</td><td>Maid Arrangement, CR</td><td>High (field, supplier visits)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Customer Management</td><td>CRM App</td><td>Customer Relations, Customer Care</td><td>High (calls, visits)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Request Management</td><td>Request Work Queue App</td><td>CR, Maid Arrangement, Customer Care</td><td>Very High</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Private Inquiries</td><td>Inquiry App or CRM sub-module</td><td>Customer Relations</td><td>High (push notifications)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Finance</td><td>Finance App</td><td>Finance</td><td>Medium (approval on mobile)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Tasks</td><td>Tasks App (cross-request queue)</td><td>All departments</td><td>Very High</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Supplier Management</td><td>Supplier App</td><td>Maid Arrangement, Finance</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Reports</td><td>Analytics App / HQ dashboard</td><td>Admin, Finance</td><td>Low</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Administration</td><td>Tenant Admin App (Olircore console)</td><td>Platform admin, agency admin</td><td>Low</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Customer portal (prototype)</td><td>Customer Mobile App</td><td>End customers</td><td>Very High</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>6.2 Minimum viable app split (recommended Phase 1)</h3>
<p>Do not launch ten apps on day one. Start with four experience apps on one backend:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Agency Hub</strong> — auth, nav, notifications, deep links into other apps</li>
  <li><strong>Request App</strong> — work queue, request detail, current action, tasks (your cleaned Request Management)</li>
  <li><strong>Customer App</strong> — customer-facing mobile (profiles, requests, payments, inquiries)</li>
  <li><strong>Finance App</strong> — invoices, payment confirmation, outstanding (or Finance section inside Hub until volume justifies split)</li>
</ol>
<p>Maid and CRM can remain sections inside Agency Hub initially, then split when teams and release cadence require independence.</p>

<h3>6.3 How apps stay linked without being one app</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Deep links:</strong> Request App → tap Customer → opens CRM App at <code>customer/{id}</code></li>
  <li><strong>Shared auth session:</strong> Single sign-on (SSO) across all apps via platform identity</li>
  <li><strong>Domain events:</strong> Payment confirmed in Finance App → Request App updates status via push or poll</li>
  <li><strong>Unified notification inbox:</strong> “Task assigned to Maid Arrangement” opens correct app and record</li>
  <li><strong>Consistent record IDs:</strong> <code>REQ-2024-041</code> is the same everywhere (your prototype standard)</li>
</ul>

<h2>7. Mobile Adoption Strategy</h2>

<h3>7.1 Recommended technical approach</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Option</th><th>Fit for MAIDCONNECT</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>PWA + responsive web (Phase 1)</strong></td><td>Best immediate path</td><td>Reuse UX patterns from prototype; installable on phones; one codebase per app</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>React Native / Flutter (Phase 2)</strong></td><td>Customer App + field staff</td><td>Push notifications, offline queue, camera for documents</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Native iOS/Android (Phase 3+)</strong></td><td>Only if market demands</td><td>Higher cost; justify with offline-heavy field use</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Your prototype is already mobile-aware in layout thinking; moving to PWA wrappers per app is the lowest-risk bridge to “business as a mobile.”</p>

<h3>7.2 Mobile-specific capabilities to plan</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Push notifications (inquiry reply, payment request, task assigned, status change)</li>
  <li>Offline task list with sync (field staff in poor connectivity)</li>
  <li>Camera upload for payment proof, maid documents, customer ID</li>
  <li>Biometric login for agency staff apps</li>
  <li>Customer App: share profile cards, WhatsApp handoff (prototype already hints at this)</li>
</ul>

<h3>7.3 API-first rule</h3>
<p>Every screen action in the prototype (assign maid, confirm payment, complete task, convert inquiry) must become an API command on a domain service. Mobile apps never implement business rules locally except for optimistic UI and queued offline actions.</p>

<div class="pagebreak"></div>

<h2>8. Multi-Company (Multi-Tenant) Design</h2>

<h3>8.1 Tenant isolation</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Every record carries <code>tenantId</code> (company)</li>
  <li>Users belong to one or more tenants with role per tenant</li>
  <li>APIs enforce tenant scope server-side — not UI dropdowns alone</li>
  <li>Customer App users see only their customer account within one tenant</li>
</ul>

<h3>8.2 Same platform, different models — worked example</h3>
<p><strong>Tenant: ABC Agency (UAE)</strong> — uses OMP “Standard Maid Placement”:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Payment gate before stage 2</li>
  <li>Departments: CR owns request until assignment; Maid Arrangement owns preparation stages</li>
  <li>Modules: full pack including Supplier and Reports</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Tenant: XYZ Domestic Services (Oman)</strong> — uses OMP “Lightweight Placement”:</p>
<ul>
  <li>No advance gate; deposit on assignment only</li>
  <li>Shorter pipeline (no separate Training stage)</li>
  <li>Modules: Maid, Customer, Request, Finance only</li>
</ul>
<p>Both use the same Request App binary from the app store; on login, the app loads XYZ’s OMP and hides disabled modules and stages.</p>

<h3>8.3 Holding group / franchise scenario</h3>
<p>If one business owns multiple brands:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Option A: one tenant per brand (simplest isolation)</li>
  <li>Option B: one tenant, multiple branches with branch-scoped data</li>
  <li>HQ Analytics App aggregates across tenants with consent and data sharing policies</li>
</ul>

<h2>9. Phased Adoption Roadmap</h2>

<h3>Phase 0 — Foundation (0–3 months)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Freeze prototype as UX/reference (no production traffic)</li>
  <li>Document entity graph and API contract from prototype (Request, Maid, Customer, etc.)</li>
  <li>Build backend: PostgreSQL (or similar), Request Service as first domain service</li>
  <li>Implement tenant + user + RBAC server-side</li>
  <li>Migrate single Request source of truth pattern from <code>RequestAPI</code> to API</li>
</ul>

<h3>Phase 1 — Agency web platform (3–6 months)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Rebuild Agency Hub as modular web app (not 6K-line HTML)</li>
  <li>Request Work Queue + Customer CRM + Finance modules on shared API</li>
  <li>Operational Model Profile v1 (stages + payment gate per tenant)</li>
  <li>Replace prototype role switcher with real auth</li>
  <li>Customer web portal on same APIs</li>
</ul>

<h3>Phase 2 — Mobile experiences (6–12 months)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>PWA or React Native Customer App</li>
  <li>Request + Tasks mobile app for agency staff</li>
  <li>Push notifications and deep linking between apps</li>
  <li>Offline queue for task completion</li>
</ul>

<h3>Phase 3 — Independent app ecosystem (12–18 months)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Split Maid App, Finance App, Supplier App where teams need separate release cycles</li>
  <li>Marketplace of OMP templates (industry packs)</li>
  <li>Partner integrations (accounting, SMS, WhatsApp Business API)</li>
  <li>Olircore admin console for onboarding new companies with chosen model</li>
</ul>

<h3>Phase 4 — Platform business (18+ months)</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Other verticals reuse platform core (same departments pattern, different entity labels)</li>
  <li>White-label Customer App per tenant</li>
  <li>API access for third-party developers</li>
</ul>

<h2>10. Mapping Prototype Patterns to Platform Services</h2>

<table>
  <tr><th>Prototype pattern</th><th>Production service</th><th>Action</th></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MaidConnectERP.registerOrder()</code></td><td>POST /tenants/{id}/requests</td><td>Implement as Request Service command</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>RequestAPI.syncProjections()</code></td><td>Read models / materialized views</td><td>Agency list and customer portal are CQRS views, not separate writes</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>MC_ACCESS</code> / <code>canAction()</code></td><td>Policy service (OPA or custom)</td><td>Evaluate on every API call</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>WorkflowEngine.propagate()</code></td><td>Event bus (Kafka, SNS, or lightweight internal)</td><td>Invalidate caches, send push, update dashboards</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>shareProfile()</code></td><td>Share Service</td><td>Owns visibility; Customer App subscribes</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>recordFinance()</code></td><td>Finance Service</td><td>Owns payment state; Request reads summary only</td></tr>
  <tr><td><code>addTask()</code> cross-department</td><td>Task Service</td><td>Department field + assignee; no request ownership change</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Role dashboards</td><td>Analytics / widget API</td><td>Per-role KPI queries on live data</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>11. Governance &amp; Rules to Prevent Prototype Mistakes at Scale</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>One writer per entity</strong> — only the owning service mutates Maid, Payment, Request canonical state.</li>
  <li><strong>No duplicate status fields</strong> — customer portal and agency portal read the same Request record version.</li>
  <li><strong>Configuration over code</strong> — new company model = new OMP, not a fork of the codebase.</li>
  <li><strong>Apps are thin</strong> — business rules live in domain services, not duplicated in each app.</li>
  <li><strong>Version OMPs</strong> — changing pipeline for Tenant A does not affect Tenant B; audit which OMP version processed each request.</li>
  <li><strong>Event contract stability</strong> — apps depend on event schemas, not internal database tables of other services.</li>
</ol>

<h2>12. Risks &amp; Mitigations</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Risk</th><th>Impact</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Too many apps too early</td><td>Integration cost explodes</td><td>Start with Hub + Request + Customer; split later</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Per-tenant customization becomes code forks</td><td>Unmaintainable platform</td><td>Strict OMP configuration boundary</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Weak API design</td><td>Mobile apps replicate prototype duplication</td><td>API review board; entity ownership matrix (Section 4.2)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Ignoring offline/mobile constraints</td><td>Field staff rejection</td><td>Task App offline-first in Phase 2</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Security as UI-only (prototype habit)</td><td>Data leaks across tenants</td><td>Server RBAC from day one of backend</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>13. Success Metrics</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Time to onboard a new company with a chosen operational model (target: days, not months)</li>
  <li>Number of apps a staff member needs daily (target: 1–2 with deep links)</li>
  <li>Request status consistency: agency vs customer portal mismatch rate = 0%</li>
  <li>Percentage of field actions completed on mobile vs desktop</li>
  <li>API response time for Request Work Queue on 4G networks</li>
  <li>Tenant configuration changes without code deployment</li>
</ul>

<h2>14. Conclusion</h2>
<p>Your plan — <strong>build the business as a mobile platform of linked apps, with stable departments but configurable operational models per company</strong> — aligns strongly with what MAIDCONNECT has already demonstrated in prototype form. The prototype’s recent architecture direction (single Request record, module ownership, unified permissions, cross-department tasks, linked views instead of duplicated profiles) is exactly the discipline required for a multi-app platform.</p>
<p>The adoption path is not to grow the HTML file into a mobile app. It is to:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Extract the <strong>entity graph and department model</strong> as the platform standard.</li>
  <li>Implement <strong>domain services with APIs</strong> as the system of record.</li>
  <li>Introduce <strong>Operational Model Profiles</strong> so each company configures workflow without forking code.</li>
  <li>Ship <strong>focused mobile experience apps</strong> that function independently but share identity, events, and record IDs.</li>
</ol>
<p>MAIDCONNECT becomes the first <strong>vertical product</strong> on the Olircore platform — maid agency — proving the model before extending the same pattern to other service businesses with the same department skeleton.</p>

